theorem Topology.closure_diff_interior_subset_frontier {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X]
    {A : Set X} :
    closure ((A \ interior A) : Set X) ⊆ frontier (A : Set X) := by
  intro x hx
  -- 1. `x` belongs to `closure A` because `A \ interior A ⊆ A`.
  have hx_clA : (x : X) ∈ closure (A : Set X) := by
    have hSub : ((A \ interior A) : Set X) ⊆ (A : Set X) := by
      intro y hy; exact hy.1
    exact (closure_mono hSub) hx
  -- 2. Show that `x` is *not* in `interior A`.
  have hx_not_int : x ∉ interior (A : Set X) := by
    intro hxInt
    -- Use the characterization of closure with open neighbourhoods.
    have hNonempty :
        ((interior (A : Set X)) ∩ (A \ interior A) : Set X).Nonempty := by
      have h := (mem_closure_iff.1 hx) isOpen_interior hxInt
      simpa [Set.inter_comm] using h
    rcases hNonempty with ⟨y, ⟨hyInt, hyDiff⟩⟩
    exact (hyDiff.2) hyInt
  -- Combine the two facts to obtain membership in the frontier.
  exact And.intro hx_clA hx_not_int

theorem Topology.dense_interior_implies_interior_closure_interior_eq_univ
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} :
    Dense (interior (A : Set X)) →
      interior (closure (interior A)) = (Set.univ : Set X) := by
  intro hDense
  have h : closure (interior (A : Set X)) = (Set.univ : Set X) := hDense.closure_eq
  simpa [h, interior_univ]

theorem Topology.interior_subset_interior_union {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A B : Set X} :
    (interior (A : Set X)) ⊆ interior (A ∪ B) := by
  intro x hx
  -- Since `A ⊆ A ∪ B`, monotonicity of `interior` yields the claim.
  have hSub : (A : Set X) ⊆ A ∪ B := by
    intro y hy
    exact Or.inl hy
  exact (interior_mono hSub) hx
